column1: Before 1 July 2022, will the CPTPP Commission decide to commence the accession process for the People's Republic of China (PRC) and/or Taiwan?
column5: ['Yes, but only for the PRC', 'Yes, but only for Taiwan', 'Yes, for both', 'No']
column6: ['Business', 'Economic Policy', 'Foreign Policy', 'Non-US Politics']
July 1st feels too soon, politically.

With only 2 months left I am getting twitchy that this wont happen in time. I am still confident that the accession process will be initiated for Taiwan at least but maybe they are waiting for UK to complete the process which is expected this year.
Informed thumbsuck
Probably no action will be taken. If one or the other is commenced, relations will deteriorate further. Both is unlikely because of current tensions between the world and PRC.
The situation is too tense to make such a provocative move
China (PRC) is a feared economic giant. But it has made many enemies in the CPTPP by shoving it weight around. The group will not want to rock the boat/
This is such a political hot potato that I cannot see a good solution. If in doubt do nothing.
I reduced my Yes answers this forecast. Just getting a bit twitchy on my gap to crowd.

The PRC will very strenously pursue this and so will Taiwan. But since all members of the CPTPP have to agree, the obstacles are very high. https://mcmillan.ca/insights/chinas-arduous-path-to-cptpp-accession-a-myriad-of-obstacles-with-an-improbable-outcome/

Reminder to look for action following APEC meeting on Nov 12. Running both off against each other sounds like a good strategy if you listen to this commentator: https://asia.nikkei.com/Opinion/How-to-make-China-and-Taiwan-earn-their-admission-to-CPTPP
CPTPP kicks the can down the road. China's wolf-diplomacy has alienated many current members, who would need to accede to PRC membership.

Not likely that the countries will even process Taiwan's request. On the other hand, CPTPP can become compatible to China's own goals towards changing their economic model. The possible "no", is when the US is also involved to join, although that doesn't seem as likely for now.

I am having trouble with the compound question Forget about the both but include this into the single. I had given 73% chance for taiwan to start and 58 % chance for China. Is this too high? Maybe Have dropped to 69 and 52. Rules clearly stipulate that separate customs territories, like Taiwan, can be members and seeing as they already align better with the trade rules I have them higher

China put in their bid on 16 Sep, Taiwan on 22 Sep. China rushed to get in first. Japan, Canada, Australia, and New Zealand had given positive responses to Taiwan’s bid Japan is chairing the CPTPP this year which may help Taiwan's bid https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/4307802 There are a lot of barriers for China but would these be addressed before or after the accession process has commenced? https://www.mic-cust.com/insights/posts/detail/ad/the-barriers-blocking-chinas-entry-to-cptpp/

Beijing needs the agreement of the eleven members of the CPTPP to join its ranks. The CPTPP involves high level rules that govern services, investment, intellectual property, digital trade and state-owned enterprises. There are commitments to liberalisation, inhibition of government interference and business protection. Beijing may have problems complying with these plus the issues concerning labour rights, the Uighurs and the repression in Hong Kong. There have also been problems over trade with Australia due to questions over the origin of Covid-19 and political detentions of Canadians to force the release of the Meng Wanzhou, chief financial officer of Huawei detained over fraud charges in the U.S. Mainland China has also reacted vociferously to Taiwan’s application to join the trade agreement, by making its position clear as to its opposition to all official interactions with or accession to any agreement with Taiwan. This is as a non-member to the CPTPP and may be considered presumptuous by the members of the trade agreement. Although there is precedence here where China that Taiwan was only allowed to join the WHO as a separate customs territory and only after China had obtained its membership. Taiwan has had progress over trade agreements with the U.S. and the EU who are both willing to support it over its stance with democracy and free market policies. One member who will perhaps support China’s bid for membership and be against Taiwan’s bid will be New Zealand who has shown a willingness to maintain fruitful relations with China over its status as its largest trade partner that has managed to disturb the other members of the ‘Five Eyes’ intelligence grouping. Therefore, given China’s probable non-compliance (and perhaps belligerence and bellicose statements/ actions) and New Zealand’s pragmatism over the protection of its major export market, neither China or Taiwan will gain membership of the CPTPP.

To allow only the PRC to proceed seems unlikely at this time with ongoing issues and that trump's tariffs remain in place. To only allow Taiwan to proceed indeed pokes the bear or the dragon as mentioned by @super_duperduh Allowing both to proceed would be very difficult politically as they work through the UK request to go forward. Betting no to both.

China will obviously fail by inspection, mostly Australia who will reject. However, at this point or at least not yet, no country is willing to poke the dragon with accession of Taiwan. They should, they will not.
